snippet.textDisplay: The reason your pour art is coming out overly dark or muddy is twofold. If you lay down a layer of white or black your paints will stay brighter, but will also mix a bit with the white or black, also over agitation, basically you are messing with it to much trying to get it perfect. It’s hard to give up control but that’s what pour art is all about letting what ever happens happen. You will find your technique the more you do, like any art style or really anything at all practice makes perfect.
snippet.textOriginal: The reason your pour art is coming out overly dark or muddy is twofold. If you lay down a layer of white or black your paints will stay brighter, but will also mix a bit with the white or black, also over agitation, basically you are messing with it to much trying to get it perfect. It’s hard to give up control but that’s what pour art is all about letting what ever happens happen. You will find your technique the more you do, like any art style or really anything at all practice makes perfect.
